The paper discusses a method for specifying and verifying software components, which falls under the umbrella of software engineering (cs.SE). The method involves using contracts, which are a common tool in programming languages and software engineering, and extends them with a notion of model, which could be seen as a form of programming language semantics (cs.PL). The paper also discusses the formal foundations of the method, which involves logic and set theory (cs.LO), and the experiments involve testing the method on libraries of data structures, which could be seen as a form of programming language implementation (cs.FL). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of the method for the accuracy of software specifications, which could be seen as a form of machine learning or artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
